What This Code Does
The provided code creates a static mini-dashboard (web application) that acts as an interactive cheat sheet for developers. Specifically, it simplifies the process of setting up a new React project using Vite.

Here is exactly how the files work together:

index.html builds a clean, dark-mode user interface consisting of a card with three sequential buttons (Steps 1, 2, and 3) and a dark mockup terminal box at the bottom.

style.css adds visual polish, giving the buttons a slight "press" effect (scale(0.98)) when clicked and changing the text highlight color to a glowing cyan.

app.js contains the logic. It listens for clicks on those buttons and dynamically swaps out the text inside the terminal box to show the exact terminal command needed for that step.

How It Improves Day-to-Day Life
While this specific app is tailored to remember Vite commands for class, the underlying concept of creating personal mini-tools significantly improves a developer's day-to-day workflow in several ways:

Eliminates Context Switching & Brain Drain: Instead of leaving your workspace to search through cluttered documentation, bookmarks, or browser history to find exact terminal flags, a custom cheat sheet keeps your most-used commands in one centralized, accessible place.

Reduces Syntax Errors: Commands like npm create vite@latest my-react-app -- --template react have highly specific syntax. By having a tool where you can click and instantly copy (select-all) the text, you eliminate typos, missing dashes, or forgotten directory names.

Streamlines Project Onboarding: If you work across multiple frameworks (e.g., Next.js, Vite, Docker, or Python virtual environments), you can expand this app into a personal developer portal. Launching a new sandbox environment goes from a multi-step mental check to a 5-second process.
